The more I travel, the more I realize there are countless places I could call home. I know it might be cheesy to post this while wearing a $20 Kimono I bought at the night market but it‚Äôs true. Every day I feel less tied to one location and more open to different cultures, foods and people. 
Right now @whatthechic @melissa @aleporte and I are exploring #SouthKorea and this is definitely a city I want to live in for a month or so. It has so much to offer and the food has been mind blowing. 
I highly recommend you take the opportunity to do a school exchange, work placement or gap year abroad to see another destination and to become a local there. It will change your perspective of the world for the better.

One of our flaws is that we only value things that feel scarce. Daily routines can often lose meaning and value when they feel limitless. Sometimes even a beautiful sunset on the way home from work can feel unimportant because ‚Äúthere will always be another‚Äù. A few years ago I began reminding myself every single time I watched the sunset that it could literally be the last time I ever witness it. 
I have never had a greater appreciation for the way the colours change and the sunlight bounces. I try to apply this same thinking to everything that I do and it has always brought a greater appreciation for the moments and things around me. 
Even if it‚Äôs from the drivers seat of your car on the way home from work, watch your next sunset like it could be your last and I can guarantee you, you will have a new found appreciation for the colours in the sky üåÖ

Deep in the crater of a Volcano üåã 
Mount Ijen is home to some of the most hard-working / badass people on planet earth. The Indonesian miners spend 9-12 hours a day carrying these baskets of Sulphur up and down the treacherous mountain while inhaling this nearly solid yellow smoke. When filled, the baskets will weigh around 100Kg / 220lbs. I could hardly lift the baskets on to my shoulders and men as old as 70 were carrying them through the steepest of climbs. On average, these men will earn around 20 USD per day. Think twice next time you complain about your job ‚õè

By far my craziest adventure yet has been sailing the Shtandart around Ireland. Three months ago I received an email from a Russian sailor inviting me to join his team on their expedition across Europe and I immediately asked myself, what would Jim Carrey do? So I said yes man. For the past week I have been swabbing the deck, manning the sails from 12pm to 4am and climbing 40 feet up into the crows nest. This has been no vacation but in doing these crazy things we create memories worth remembering. This week I learned "Daah" means yes, Russians love mayonnaise and that I only sorta get sea sick when rocking back and forth for hours in a small storm. Check my insta story for BTS üçÄ

Instagram is Dangerous. Usually I would caption something along the lines of "bathing in the clouds" but I thought I would take a different direction on this one. 
The other day I was listening to my pastor talk about the dangers of constantly showing people our best sides. I immediately felt conflicted by this message because in a sense, that is my job. Nobody wants to watch a video called "Mediocre day in Thailand" or like a photo of a 3 star hotel. As content creators, we are constantly showing our best. The danger is that what people perceive is radically different from the reality.

There are some hilarious stories of Instagram couples that you know and love taking these magical photos and captioning the "pure bliss" they experienced in that seemingly romantic moment, when in reality they were battling through the cold, arguing two seconds before hand, and probably wanted nothing more than to be at home watching Netflix. But again, that photo wouldn't be so incredible if they had captioned "would rather be anywhere else but near her/him right now" üòÇ 
Comparison is the death of all joy. Even I battle with it. It's key to remind ourselves that Instagram is an artistic representation of a moment and it only conveys what the photographer or videographers wants to portray. Enjoy Instagram for what it really is. A fun place to enjoy art, adventure and inspiration. 
What do you think? I'd love to hear.

This was a total Yes Man moment. After watching the sunrise over Angkor Wat and spending the entire day exploring temples, I was exhausted. My driver told me about a place just outside of Siem Reap where you could watch the sunset over a floating village. Everything in my body was telling me to say no but I said yes. I was so close to missing out on what was one of the most incredible sights of my entire life. Saying Yes opens doors and new adventures, saying no does not. Be a #YesMan üëäüèº Ps go watch that movie if you haven't already. It's amazing.

I remember when people used to mock me for talking to my camera or for making videos of my travels. The tough reality is that in order to be successful, you have to be different. Crew love
After 25 hours of standing in the truck, this was their immediate reaction to their new home. Boonme and Buaban's first tastes of freedom at @elephantnaturepark

After driving through the night, we arrived in Surin Thailand to purchase and rescue two abused elephants. After the money changed hands and the elephants were loaded on the truck, it was time to drive back 25 hours to Chiang Mai to bring the rescue elephants to their new home. This was the view from on top of the truck. When you visit @elephantnaturepark keep an eye open for Boonme and Buaban üêòüêò full story on YouTube - link in bio

This is the face of Chang beer. Like most elephants in Thailand, he spends his days bound to an enclosure with about 6 feet of chain. Most of the time, you will find them rocking back and forth and letting out cries of frustration and sadness. This is the result of elephant tourism. We need you to change this. Avoid trekking camps, and any form of elephant entertainment. Find the sanctuaries that allow their elephants to be elephants like @elephantnaturepark üêò The final Black Tusk vlog is live. Can't wait to share the documentary @blakedavey and I have been working on. Should be out in December. #BlackTusk

Easily the coolest person I have ever met. Lek is @Time Magazines "Hero of Asia" for her work in elephant conservation. Today she has rescued over 200 üêò from logging, begging, and the tourism industry. You have not seen love until you've seen Lek sing an elephant to sleep. Vlog 2 is up from @elephantnaturepark Link in bio.

Black Tusk is my biggest and certainly most meaningful project yet. Two weeks ago, @blakedavey and I set out to Thailand to show people the horrible abuse elephants face in the trekking industry. Most tourist do not realize that elephants who perform or are used to give rides have been tortured and taken away from their friends and families. Fortunately, we have the ability to end this. By supporting elephant sanctuaries like @elephantnaturepark you are directly shifting a tourism industry for the better. Black Tusk is not yet completed and won't be for about a couple months but the first vlog is up. See for yourself what happy elephants look like by clicking the link in my bio. Make sure to tell your friends to chose sanctuaries and to avoid elephant trekking/entertainment businesses at all costs. Shouts to @carlyfairbank for the sick font üêò #blacktusk

What does it mean to #GetLost ? For me, it mean't walking away from a job that guaranteed financial wealth and dependable job security. It mean't prematurely canceling my lease and temporarily moving back home with my parents. But most of all, it mean't unconditionally following my passion regardless of how uncertain that path was. 
In the 6+ months I have lived my life this way, I have never been so happy and fulfilled. Getting lost and veering from the traditional path was the best thing I could have ever done. I challenge everyone to ask more from their lives. It's not easy, but when you do things that others would not, you find the greatest opportunities. Create your own path and #GetLost

It's official! I have resigned from my corporate "dream job" and I'll be returning to Asia in the new year. 2016 will be all about pursuing my passion.

After my 8 month adventure around the world, I started working an amazing job downtown, but everyday I would be left wondering if there wasn't something more I could have done with social media. Everyday I would weigh the pros and cons of following this uncertain career path until I could no longer deny the fact that this is what I need to do. 
I have found something I am truly motivated by. Something that gets me out of bed in the morning and I would be foolish not to give this opportunity everything I have. 
I don't know how I will afford it or where this will take me, but one thing I know is that 2016 is about living life to the fullest extent.
